                        <div class="visually-hidden">
                <span itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">Morning Agenda: Executive Strategy at Bank of America</span>
                <span class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
                    By Amie Tsang                </span>
                <!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2015-07-28T11:07:45+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">July 28, 2015 7:07 am</time>
			<!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">July 28, 2015 7:07 am</span>            </div>
			<div class="entry-content">
			<div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="//news.blogs.nytimes.com/2015/07/28/morning-agenda-executive-strategy-at-bank-of-america/" data-title="Morning Agenda: Executive Strategy at Bank of America" data-description="Thwarting the Quick Buck | Bigger is Better in Pharmaceuticals | Greek Preparations for Euro Exit">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><div class="round-up">
<div class="ru-top-story">
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"><strong>EXECUTIVE STRATEGY AT BANK OF AMERICA</strong> <span class="divider"> | </span></span> Bruce Thompson, Bank of Americaâs former chief financial officer, had taken a victory lap just days before he was ousted from his job. His <b>departure stunned investors</b>, <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/07/28/business/dealbook/executive-departure-draws-attention-to-bank-of-americas-growth-strategy.html?ref=dealbook">Julie Creswell and Michael Corkery report in DealBook</a>. âI havenât spoken to anyone who isnât surprised,â said Mike Mayo, a CLSA banking analyst, who has a sell rating on the bank. âItâs a head-scratcher.â </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> The move has also highlighted the burden on the chief executive Brian T. Moynihan, who is under ever greater pressure to expand the bank while integrating disparate businesses and personalities. Executives at other banks were able to bolster profits more easily by shedding businesses and cutting costs, but Mr. Moynihan was stuck managing the <b>enormous financial and legal fallout</b> from two transformational mergers undertaken by his predecessor: the acquisitions of the mortgage lender Countryside and the investment banking giant Merrill Lynch. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> Bank of Americaâs <b>stock performance has lagged</b> that of other megabanks, including JPMorgan Chase, Citigroup and Wells Fargo. It has taken more than $70 billion in charges to pay legal fines, settlements and penalties related to its consumer mortgage business. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> An embarrassing $4 billion error in its books also caused regulators to delay a promised stock-buyback plan. People briefed on the matter have said that Mr. Thompson, who was widely seen as a successor to Mr. Moynihan, saw <b>his star dim</b> after the accounting miscalculation. With Mr. Thompson gone, there is <b>no clear successor</b> to Mr. Moynihan. Thomas K. Montag, the chief operating officer and head of the investment bank, is not considered a likely candidate. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> âI think Moynihan has done a reasonably good job of dealing with the legacy issues, but I donât think he gets the same respect as some of his peers and my question is, is he the <b>right guy going forward?</b>&#8221; asked Jonathan Finger, a partner at the Houston-based Finger Interests, which owns about 900,000 shares of Bank of America.</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"><strong>THWARTING THE QUICK BUCK</strong> <span class="divider"> | </span></span> While there has been plenty of agitation over Hillary Rodham Clintonâs emails, there has been less focus on her ideas to <b>transform Wall Street and corporate America</b>. If Mrs. Clinton becomes president, her plans could radically change the way investors and chief executives behave, <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/07/28/business/dealbook/clinton-aim-is-to-thwart-quick-buck-on-wall-st.html?ref=dealbook">Andrew Ross Sorkin writes in the DealBook column</a>. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> As part of her efforts to end investorsâ <b>obsession with short-term results</b>, Mrs. Clinton wants to introduce a âsix-year sliding scaleâ for capital gains taxes. Individuals in the top bracket would pay ordinary income tax of 39.6 percent on the sale of investments in the first two years. The rate would decrease over the next four years to the current capital gains rate of 20 percent. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> Laurence D. Fink, the chief executive of the $4 trillion asset manager BlackRock, has proposed something similar. He has suggested applying <b>capital gains treatment</b> only after three years, then decreasing the tax rate each year after that, potentially dropping to zero after 10 years. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> Creating incentives for investors, chief executives and board directors to be less focused on quarterly profits and immediate stock prices should be a <b>boon to the economy</b>, Mr. Sorkin writes. âFrom a political perspective, itâs hard to argue with â itâs about as safe as they come.â Even the activist investor Carl C. Icahn has said, âShe is onto something.â </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> However, Mrs. Clinton has also stepped into riskier territory, hinting that she would consider the argument that <b>stock buybacks</b> could be considered stock manipulations. While that might resonate politically for some in the Democratic Party, Mr. Sorkin notes, it is likely to be a step too far.</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"><strong>BIGGER IS BETTER IN PHARMACEUTICALS</strong> <span class="divider"> | </span></span> Tevaâs $40.5 billion acquisition of Allerganâs generic drug business is its entry into the pharmaceutical arms race, <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/07/28/business/dealbook/teva-pharmaceuticals-to-buy-allergans-generics-business.html?ref=dealbook">Michael J. de la Merced writes in DealBook</a>. The drug industry has seen a surge in acquisitions in recent years as manufacturers have sought to plug holes in their product portfolios and grow. The purchases have given big drug companies <b>access to new drugs </b> in late-stage development, meaning they have new treatments without having to engage in the lengthy and often expensive process of research. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> Acquisitions also help pharmaceutical companies <b>maintain negotiating leverage</b> when their partners grow. The five biggest American health insurers may shrink to three if two big mergers announced this month are approved, and hospital systems have been merging too. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> As such, <b>big drug makers with ample cash reserves</b> are on the hunt. Pfizer, AbbVie and Allergan could all start pursuing acquisitions. Teva dropped its attempted takeover of Mylan, which has been trying to buy Perrigo, an Irish drug maker, for $34 billion. But <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/07/28/business/dealbook/tevas-deal-for-allergan-units-allows-graceful-exit-from-mylan-fray.html?ref=dealbook">Neil Unmack at Breakingviews</a> writes that, âA faster, cleaner deal with Allergan should let Teva deleverage more quickly, paving the way for more deals.â</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"><strong>ON THE AGENDA</strong> <span class="divider"> | </span></span> <b>The Committee on Financial Services</b> hearing titled âThe Dodd-Frank Act Five Years Later: Are We More Prosperous?â starts at 10 a.m. <b>Twitter</b> will release second-quarter earnings after the market closes and will discuss the results at 5 p.m. <b>BP</b> hosts a results webcast at 9 a.m. <b>Pfizer</b> will discuss results for the second quarter at 10 a.m. The <b>S&#038;P/Case-Shiller index</b> of house prices will be released at 9 a.m., followed by The Conference Boardâs report on <b>consumer confidence</b> at 10 a.m.</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"><strong>GREEK PREPARATIONS FOR EURO EXIT</strong> <span class="divider"> | </span></span> The Greek government is facing fresh criticism over <b>secret preparations</b> that would have allowed the country to leave the euro, <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/07/28/business/greece-debt-varoufakis-recording.html?ref=dealbook">Jack Ewing and Niki Kitsantonis report in The New York Times</a>. In <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/07/28/business/international/varoufakis-tapes-listen-to-excerpts-from-greeces-former-finance-minister-on-the-crisis.html?ref=international">a recording released on Monday</a>, Yanis Varoufakis, Greeceâs former finance minister, detailed a contingency plan to create an alternative banking system that could switch to a new currency. Mr. Varoufakis said Prime Minister Alexis Tsipras of Greece had authorized the preliminary plan, but did not allow the final plan to be put into action. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> Opposition members of Parliament have <b>called for an investigation</b>, putting pressure on Mr. Tsipras, who has relied on opposition support to pass legislation demanded by creditors.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> Mr. Varoufakis has defended himself in <a href="//www.ft.com/cms/s/0/27db9c44-3483-11e5-bdbb-35e55cbae175.html#ixzz3hAn0PsBL">an Op-Ed in The Financial Times</a>. âWhile I understand the pressâs excitement emanating from elements of that exchange, such as having to consider unorthodox means of gaining access to my own ministryâs systems, there is only one matter of significance from a public interest perspective. There is a <b>hideous restriction of national sovereignty</b> imposed by the troika of lenders upon Greek ministers who are denied access to departments of their ministries pivotal in implementing innovative policies.â</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story --></div>
